The ADGM evaluates the effectiveness of the systems and controls established by a start-up for managing and controlling its affairs based on the following specific criteria:

* The establishment of appropriate systems and controls that demonstrate the effective management and control of the firm's affairs (aligns with "All applicants are required to establish appropriate systems and controls to demonstrate that the affairs of the firm are managed and controlled effectively.");
* The nature and scope of the systems and controls, which may depend on the nature, size, and complexity of the business (aligns with "The nature of the systems and controls may depend on the nature, size and complexity of the business.");
* The implementation of additional systems and controls during the initial period of operation following launch, such as increased risk or compliance monitoring (aligns with "A start-up may wish to consider which additional systems and controls may be appropriate in the initial period of operation following launch, such as increased risk or compliance monitoring.");
* The imposition of restrictions on business activities or a greater degree and intensity of supervision, particularly for start-ups with an unproven track record (aligns with "Due to the unproven track record of a start-up, we may, for example, impose restrictions on the business activities of the entity or a greater degree and intensity of supervision until such a track record is established.");
* For Funds, the appointment of at least one individual other than the Senior Executive Officer to carry out Senior Manager functions, including managing operational risk and other internal controls (aligns with "In respect of a Fund, the Regulator would expect the Fund Manager to appoint at least one individual other than the Senior Executive Officer to carry out Senior Manager functions in relation to the Fund such as managing operational risk and other internal controls.");
* The formal documentation of the assignment of climate-related financial risk management responsibilities within the organization, as outlined in Principle 3 (aligns with "As outlined in Principle 1, while the financial firm’s board remains ultimately responsible and accountable for the oversight of the management of climate-related financial risks, the assignment of responsibilities in line with Principle 3 should be formally documented.").

By evaluating these criteria, the ADGM can assess the effectiveness of a start-up's systems and controls in managing and controlling its affairs, and ensure that the firm has a robust risk management framework in place.

