SPECIFIC FSRA GUIDANCE ON THE VIRTUAL ASSET FRAMEWORK
Data protection obligations for Authorised Persons
ADGM’s data protection regime protects individuals’ right to privacy by controlling how personal information is used by organisations and businesses registered in ADGM.  All entities registered in ADGM that hold or process the personal data of an individual must protect personal data in compliance with the ADGM Data Protection Regulations 2015 (the “Data Protection Regulations”).  Specifically, an Authorised Person, as a data controller, will be responsible for determining the purposes for which, and the manner in which, personal data is processed in compliance with the Data Protection Regulations. Failure to do so risks enforcement action and compensation claims from individuals, each of which are considered data subjects under the Data Protection Regulations.

Answer:
The FSRA tracks and monitors the resolution of complaints to ensure that all regulatory actions are followed through to completion by:

* Acknowledging complaints promptly, as Recognised Bodies are expected to do so when determining their effective arrangements for the investigation and resolution of complaints (source: Recognised Body's complaints procedure);
* Conducting an objective, prompt, and thorough initial investigation of complaints, which enables the FSRA to assess the matter thoroughly and provide a timely response to the complainant (source: Recognised Body's complaints procedure);
* Providing a timely reply to the complainant after the initial investigation, keeping the complainant informed of the progress and outcome of the complaint (source: Recognised Body's complaints procedure);
* Informing the complainant of their right to apply to the Recognised Body's complaints investigator, ensuring that complainants are aware of the available channels for escalation (source: Recognised Body's complaints procedure);
* Keeping adequate records of complaints and investigations, which enables the FSRA to maintain a comprehensive and accurate record of all complaints and their resolution (source: Recognised Body's complaints procedure);
* Ensuring authorised firms are fully cognisant of applicable reporting obligations under the FATCA and Common Reporting Standards regimes, which helps prevent money laundering and other financial crimes (source: Principle 3 – Preventing Money Laundering and Other Financial Crime);
* Ensuring Authorised Persons comply with data protection obligations under the ADGM Data Protection Regulations 2015, which includes determining the purposes and manner of personal data processing, and maintaining accurate records of data subjects (source: ADGM Data Protection Regulations 2015); and
* Recognising that failure to comply with data protection regulations may result in enforcement action and compensation claims from individuals, which serves as a deterrent and encourages Authorised Persons to adhere to the regulations (source: ADGM Data Protection Regulations 2015).

By following these procedures, the FSRA ensures that all regulatory actions are tracked and monitored to completion, upholding its regulatory obligations and maintaining a robust complaint resolution process.

