In deciding whether to exercise our power to disqualify an auditor or actuary under section 233(3) of FSMR, and what the scope of any disqualification will be, we will take into account all the circumstances of the case, including:
(a)	the nature and seriousness of any contravention of FSMR or Rules and the effect of that contravention;
(b)	whether any contravention of FSMR or Rules, or any failure to disclose information to us, has resulted in or is likely to result in:
(i)	loss to customers;
(ii)	damage to the reputation of the ADGM; or
(iii)	an increased risk that a firm, Recognised Body or Reporting Entity may be used for the purposes of financial crime;
(c)	any action taken by the auditor or actuary to remedy the contravention;
(d)	any disciplinary action taken (or to be taken) against the auditor or actuary by a relevant professional body, and whether that action adequately addresses the particular contravention; and
(e)	the previous compliance record of the auditor or actuary concerned, and whether the relevant regulatory body or professional body has imposed any previous disciplinary sanctions that may be relevant.

Answer:
Here is a structured answer that directly addresses the question, covering all critical regulatory obligations and avoiding any contradictions:

Upon ceasing their role, an auditor or actuary is duty-bound to communicate to the Regulator any matter connected with their cessation that they think ought to be drawn to the Regulator's attention. This includes any contravention of the Financial Services and Markets Regulations (FSMR) or Rules, or any failure to disclose information to the Regulator, that may have resulted in or is likely to result in:

* Loss to customers (Section 233(3) of FSMR);
* Damage to the reputation of the Abu Dhabi Global Market (ADGM) (Section 233(3) of FSMR);
* An increased risk that a firm, Recognised Body, or Reporting Entity may be used for the purposes of financial crime (Section 233(3) of FSMR).

Additionally, the auditor or actuary must consider the nature and seriousness of any contravention, as well as any action taken to remedy the contravention, in deciding what matters to communicate to the Regulator.

The thresholds or criteria that define the importance of such matters include:

* The severity of the contravention and its impact on customers, the ADGM's reputation, or the risk of financial crime;
* Any disciplinary action taken or to be taken by a relevant professional body, and whether that action adequately addresses the particular contravention;
* The previous compliance record of the auditor or actuary, including any previous disciplinary sanctions imposed by the relevant regulatory body or professional body.

In the context of spot commodity activities, the auditor or actuary must also consider the capital requirements applicable to the Regulated Activities engaged in using Spot Commodities, as well as other Regulated Activities under the FSRA Prudential – Investment, Insurance Intermediation and Banking Rules ("PRU"). The FSRA will apply a capital requirement that is the higher of the regulatory capital requirements applicable to these activities.

In summary, an auditor or actuary must communicate to the Regulator any matter connected with their cessation that may have resulted in or is likely to result in harm to customers, the ADGM's reputation, or an increased risk of financial crime, as well as any relevant threshold or criteria that define the importance of such matters, including the severity of the contravention, disciplinary action, and previous compliance record.

