The Abu Dhabi Global Market (ADGM) takes a robust approach to Anti-Money Laundering (AML) and Combating the Financing of Terrorism (CFT) regulations, and non-compliance with these obligations can lead to severe sanctions. According to the ADGM regulations, failure to comply with AML/CFT obligations can result in fines, penalties, and even license revocation.

To mitigate potential breaches, Authorised Persons conducting Regulated Activities in relation to Accepted Spot Commodities must consider reporting obligations under FATCA and Common Reporting Standards, as set out in the Guidance Notes on the requirements of the Intergovernmental Agreement between the United Arab Emirates and the United States and the ADGM Common Reporting Standard Regulations 2017, respectively.

In addition, Digital Investment Managers must implement robust data security policies and systems to ensure compliance with relevant data protection regulations, including the ADGM's Data Protection Regulations and PRU 6.6-6.9. This includes protecting client data and ensuring the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of such data.

Furthermore, Authorised Persons holding or Controlling Client Investments in Virtual Assets must conduct reconciliations at intervals in compliance with Rule ‎17.8.3 to ensure accurate and reliable records.

To avoid potential breaches and sanctions, Authorised Persons should:

* Establish robust AML/CFT policies and procedures, including customer due diligence, ongoing monitoring, and reporting of suspicious transactions;
* Implement effective data security measures to protect client data and prevent cyberattacks;
* Conduct regular reconciliations of Client Investments in Virtual Assets;
* Ensure compliance with reporting obligations under FATCA and Common Reporting Standards;
* Provide ongoing training to employees on AML/CFT and data protection regulations;
* Conduct regular risk assessments and audits to identify and mitigate potential breaches; and
* Implement a whistle-blower policy to report suspicious activities and potential breaches.

By taking these steps, Authorised Persons can mitigate the risk of non-compliance with AML/CFT obligations and avoid potential sanctions under ADGM regulations.

