* Adopt appropriate procedures for making and amending rules, including taking decisions about making and amending Business Rules, Clearing Rules, and Default Rules, and ensuring that decisions are taken at the appropriate level, with provision for delegation of decisions by the Governing Body ( alignments with point (a) );
* Consult users of the Recognised Body's facilities and have proper regard to any public comments received, which will help identify potential impacts on Members and stakeholders (alignment with point (b) );
* Consider the impact the proposed amendment has on the interests of its Members and other stakeholders, taking into account their diverse needs and concerns (alignment with point (c) );
* Notify Members and other stakeholders of rule amendments, ensuring transparency and timely communication (alignment with point (d) );
* Take a risk-based approach to consider whether the proposed amendment may lead to any changes in the risk assessment of customers, similar to the approach required for Customer Due Diligence (CDD) measures (alignment with 8.1.2(1) );
* Evaluate the potential impact of the proposed amendment on existing customers, considering factors such as changes in customer identity or beneficial ownership, unusual transactions, changes in the purpose or nature of the relationship, or other relevant matters that may affect the risk assessment (alignment with points (a)-(d) of 8.1.2(1) ).

By following these procedures, a Recognised Body can ensure that the impact of proposed rule amendments on Members and stakeholders is comprehensively assessed and addressed, aligning with regulatory obligations and minimizing potential risks.

